Chapter 5: Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure

Introduction to Chemical Bonds

Chemical bonds are the forces that hold atoms together in molecules and compounds. Understanding how atoms bond is fundamental to explaining the properties of matter and predicting how substances will behave in chemical reactions.

What are chemical bonds? Chemical bonds form when atoms share or transfer electrons to achieve a stable electron configuration, typically resembling that of the nearest noble gas. This process releases energy, making the bonded state more stable than separate atoms.

Types of Chemical Bonds

There are three primary types of chemical bonds: ionic bonds, covalent bonds, and metallic bonds. Each type involves electrons in different ways and produces substances with distinct properties.

Ionic Bonds

Ionic bonds form between metals and nonmetals through the transfer of electrons. When a metal atom loses one or more electrons, it becomes a positively charged ion called a cation. When a nonmetal gains those electrons, it becomes a negatively charged ion called an anion. The electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions creates the ionic bond.

Example: Sodium chloride (NaCl) forms when sodium (Na) transfers one electron to chlorine (Cl). Sodium becomes Na⁺ and chlorine becomes Cl⁻. The strong electrostatic attraction between Na⁺ and Cl⁻ ions creates table salt.

Why do ionic bonds form? The driving force is the achievement of stable electron configurations. Sodium has one valence electron and readily loses it to achieve the stable configuration of neon. Chlorine has seven valence electrons and gains one to achieve the stable configuration of argon.

Properties of ionic compounds include:
- High melting and boiling points due to strong electrostatic forces
- Brittleness because shifting ion layers causes repulsion
- Conductivity when dissolved in water or melted, as ions become mobile
- Formation of crystal lattices with regular geometric arrangements

