Covalent Bonds

Covalent bonds form when atoms share electrons rather than transfer them. This typically occurs between nonmetal atoms with similar electronegativities. The shared electrons are attracted to both atomic nuclei, holding the atoms together.

Single, double, and triple bonds: Atoms can share one pair of electrons (single bond), two pairs (double bond), or three pairs (triple bond). For example, hydrogen gas (H₂) has a single bond, oxygen gas (O₂) has a double bond, and nitrogen gas (N₂) has a triple bond.

How do we represent covalent bonds? Lewis structures show valence electrons as dots and shared pairs as lines between atoms. This visual representation helps us understand molecular structure and predict properties.

Electronegativity and bond polarity: When atoms with different electronegativities form a covalent bond, the shared electrons are pulled more strongly toward the more electronegative atom. This creates a polar covalent bond with partial positive and negative charges (δ⁺ and δ⁻).

Example: In a water molecule (H₂O), oxygen is more electronegative than hydrogen. The shared electrons spend more time near oxygen, giving it a partial negative charge (δ⁻) while the hydrogen atoms have partial positive charges (δ⁺).

