Molecular Geometry and VSEPR Theory

The shape of a molecule determines many of its properties. Valence Shell Electron Pair Repulsion (VSEPR) theory helps us predict molecular geometry based on electron pair arrangements.

According to VSEPR theory, electron pairs around a central atom repel each other and arrange themselves to minimize repulsion. This determines the three-dimensional shape of the molecule.

Common molecular geometries:
- Linear: Two electron groups (example: CO₂, 180° bond angle)
- Trigonal planar: Three electron groups (example: BF₃, 120° bond angles)
- Tetrahedral: Four electron groups (example: CH₄, 109.5° bond angles)
- Trigonal pyramidal: Four electron groups with one lone pair (example: NH₃)
- Bent: Four electron groups with two lone pairs (example: H₂O, 104.5° bond angle)

Why does molecular shape matter? Shape affects polarity, which influences solubility, boiling point, and chemical reactivity. For instance, CO₂ is linear and nonpolar despite having polar bonds because the bond dipoles cancel out. In contrast, H₂O is bent and polar because the bond dipoles do not cancel.

